<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the table-level READ ACL that
    grants the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_manager` UNCONDITIONAL read access
    on records of the `x_casemgmt_case` custom table inside the scoped
    application `x_casemgmt`. This is the READ companion to the case_manager
    create / write / delete ACLs (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_manager.xml,
    ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_manager.xml, ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_delete_manager.xml)
    and together those four files materialize the AAP Section 0.5.6 row:
    "x_casemgmt_case_manager : Create=Yes, Read=All, Write=All, Delete=Yes."

    The case_manager role is the highest-tier scoped role for case-management
    operations; per AAP Section 0.5.6 the manager has UNRESTRICTED read
    privileges on every case row regardless of who originally opened the
    case, who is currently assigned to it, or which group owns it. Read is
    the foundation privilege on which every other manager privilege builds:
    a manager cannot triage, route, prioritize, or escalate a case without
    first being able to see it, and they cannot drive the Resolved -> Closed
    transition (reserved to the manager role per AAP Section 0.5.5) without
    first reading the case to confirm its current status. This file is
    therefore the prerequisite ACL for every other manager-tier capability.

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - case_manager row (verbatim from AAP):
            | Role                    | Create | Read | Write | Delete |
            | x_casemgmt_case_manager  |  Yes   | All  |  All  |  Yes   |
        This file authors the single "Read = All" cell. The "Yes" Create
        cell is authored by ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_manager.xml; the
        "All" Write cell by ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_manager.xml; the
        "Yes" Delete cell by ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_delete_manager.xml. Each
        row of the ACL matrix maps to exactly one or zero ACL XML files -
        this per-cell granularity is what lets the Update Set add or remove
        role privileges independently without entangling roles or operations.
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - all-roles read coverage on x_casemgmt_case:
            - case_manager: Read=All            -> THIS FILE
            - case_agent:   Read=Assigned only  -> ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned.xml
                                                   (carries the row-level filter
                                                    "assigned_agent = current.sys_id
                                                     OR assigned_group IN
                                                     current.user_group_membership")
            - case_viewer:  Read=All            -> ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_viewer.xml
                                                   (also unconditional - viewer is
                                                    the audit / supervisor tier)
        Together these three facts implement the user prompt's contract:
        the manager and viewer both see every case unconditionally (manager
        for operational oversight, viewer for audit / compliance review);
        the agent's read scope is narrowed to "Assigned only" so agents see
        only the cases they are entitled to work on. The deny-by-default
        nature of ServiceNow record ACLs means a user with NO scoped role
        sees zero rows on the case table; the three read ACLs combined give
        each role exactly its prescribed visibility.
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - relationship between this table-level
        read ACL and the field-level ACLs on assigned_group / assigned_agent:
            - ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml restricts
              WRITE on the assigned_group column.
            - ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml restricts
              WRITE on the assigned_agent column.
        Those field-level ACLs constrain WRITE only - they do NOT narrow
        READ visibility. Per the AAP matrix every role with Read=All can
        see every column on every visible row, including the sensitive
        assignment columns. This is intentional: managers must see who is
        currently assigned to a case before they can re-route it; viewers
        must see assignment data for compliance and oversight. Therefore
        this READ ACL is unconditional at both the table level (no row
        filter) and the field level (no per-column read restriction).
      - Section 0.5.5 (State-Machine Transition Map) - manager-driven
        transitions that depend on this ACL:
            - "Resolved -> Closed: Caller has x_casemgmt_case_manager role;
               auto-set closed_date." Closing a case requires the manager
               to FIRST read the case to confirm it is in Resolved status
               and to confirm all child x_casemgmt_case_task records are
               status=Closed (the task-closure check is encoded in
               ../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml and
               in ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml).
               The read of the parent case row is authorized by THIS ACL.
            - "Any forward transition" by the manager: every UI Action and
               flow-driven transition begins with the manager opening a
               case form, which is itself a read operation. Without this
               ACL the case form would not load and no transition could
               ever fire.
        The transition rules are validated by the two case-type Flow
        Designer flows ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml and
        ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml plus the supporting subflows
        under ../flows/sub_flows/; those flows fire AFTER the platform's
        ACL evaluator has authorized the underlying read, so this ACL is
        a prerequisite to the flow ever running for a manager.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 - ACLs):
            "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot write;
             case_agent cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager has
             full access."
        The clause "case_manager has full access" requires that the manager
        role be able to perform every CRUD operation on the case table; of
        the four operations, READ is the most-frequent and the entry point
        to all interactive workflows. This ACL satisfies that clause for
        the read operation; the parallel clauses about case_viewer (which
        also reads all per the matrix - the AAP only restricts case_viewer
        from WRITE / CREATE / DELETE) and case_agent (read-restricted to
        "Assigned only") are unaffected by this ACL and are enforced by
        separate sibling ACL files.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 1 - Data model):
            "All 3 custom tables created with correct fields and types -
             Zero missing mandatory fields."
        This validation is performed in part by a logged-in test user
        opening the case form to inspect the field set. The validation plan
        in ../docs/validation-gates.md exercises the demo manager
        (../seed-data/users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml) reading
        each demo case to verify all twelve case fields render correctly
        (number, type, status, priority, subject, description, opened_date,
        closed_date, assigned_group, assigned_agent, requester_name,
        requester_email - per AAP Section 0.5.7). Every one of those reads
        is authorized by THIS ACL.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 4 - Portal Submission)
        and Gate 5 (Portal Lookup): although the portal pages run as the
        platform-default elevated user (NOT as case_manager), the
        post-submit verification step ("Case appears in internal list with
        Draft status and correct case number") is performed by an
        authenticated internal manager session reading the case list. That
        list-rendering operation is authorized by THIS ACL.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 6 - Dashboards):
            "Both dashboards render with synthetic data - All widgets
             display data; no broken report references."
        The Manager View dashboard (../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_manager_view.xml)
        composes five reports - cases by status bar, cases by type donut,
        cases by priority bar, average time to close single score, cases
        opened in last 30 days single score (AAP Section 0.4.4) - each of
        which is rendered for the demo manager. Every report execution
        triggers a GlideRecord query against x_casemgmt_case which is
        evaluated against this ACL; any restriction here would cause some
        reports to under-count rows and the dashboard validation would
        fail. Manager Read=All is therefore required for accurate
        organization-wide aggregates.
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications - Scoped role-based
        access control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and
        field-level ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL
        expressions, replacing ArkCase's ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig
        map." This ACL is the table-level READ binding for the highest-tier
        scoped role and is one of the declarative facts the platform's
        sys_security_acl evaluator consumes when authorizing a row read at
        runtime.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Technical Interpretation - Access-control
        transformation): "ApplicationRolesConfig + RolesPrivilegesService +
        URL-based privilege metadata -> scoped roles + ACLs." In ArkCase
        the equivalent of THIS file would have been a single entry in the
        rolesToPrivileges map binding the manager-equivalent role to a
        privilege identifier such as `acm-case-read` or `acm-case-view`,
        evaluated at HTTP request time by AcmPluginUrlPrivilege against
        the GET verb on the casefile REST endpoint. The ServiceNow target
        replaces both the map binding and the URL-privilege evaluator with
        this single declarative ACL record; the platform's sys_security_acl
        engine handles the role-membership check, condition evaluation, and
        admin-override logic that ArkCase implemented through hand-written
        Java code (see acm-services/acm-service-users plus the admin-plugin
        Java REST controllers under acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/
        acm-admin-plugin/.../web/api/).

    Why advanced=false (no scripted condition for manager read):
      Per AAP Section 0.5.6, the case_manager role's privileges are
      unconditional ("All", "Full access") - there is no "Assigned only"
      or other row-level filter. The manager is intentionally NOT scoped
      to a subset of cases; they have org-wide read authority because
      their job function is exactly to oversee, route, and close cases
      across all assignment boundaries. Therefore:
        - <advanced>false</advanced>      - no scripted condition
        - <condition/>                    - empty encoded query (no row filter)
        - <script/>                       - empty server-side script
      With no condition and no script, the ACL evaluates to "permit" for
      any caller who carries the x_casemgmt_case_manager role. This is the
      correct semantic for the AAP's "manager has full read" requirement.
      Setting advanced=true with an empty script would be functionally
      equivalent but stylistically incorrect - the ServiceNow convention
      is to reserve advanced=true for ACLs that actually carry a scripted
      body (see, for contrast, ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned.xml
      where advanced=true and the script encodes the disjunctive ownership
      check `current.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID() ||
      gs.getUser().isMemberOf(current.assigned_group)`).

    Why READ is granted to manager unconditionally (design rationale):
      - Operational oversight: managers must see every case to triage
        intake, balance group workloads, identify stuck cases, escalate
        priority cases, and re-route mis-classified cases. Restricting
        manager read to "Assigned only" would defeat the entire purpose
        of having a manager tier - they would only see cases someone else
        had already routed to them, and by definition they could not
        ROUTE cases between agents (the WRITE companion) without first
        being able to READ candidate destinations.
      - State-machine entry point: per AAP Section 0.5.5 several
        transitions are reserved to or driven by the manager role
        (Resolved -> Closed; cross-team Open re-routing). Every transition
        begins by the manager opening a case form to inspect current state
        - that form-load is a READ authorized by this ACL. Without this
        ACL no manager could ever drive any transition.
      - Reporting accuracy: the Manager View dashboard (AAP Section 0.4.4)
        aggregates organization-wide case counts by status, type, and
        priority. Those aggregates are computed via GlideRecord queries
        that evaluate this ACL on every row; any narrowing of manager
        read would distort the aggregates and break Gate 6 of the
        validation framework.
      - Audit and compliance support: managers may be called upon to
        produce a report or pull a case file for legal, compliance, or
        executive review at any time, on any case. The unconditional read
        ensures they can answer those requests without privilege
        escalation requests to platform admins.
      - Demo-data lifecycle: the seed script ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js
        creates ten demo cases spanning all six statuses and both case
        types (AAP Section 0.4.1). The smoke-test phase requires the
        demo manager (../seed-data/users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml)
        to read all ten cases to confirm seed completeness; that read is
        authorized by THIS ACL.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section
    0.3.2; no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these
    files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/services/
        users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single configuration
        map (`Map<String, List<Object>> rolesToPrivileges`) keyed by the
        property `application.rolesToPrivileges`. The class declares the
        constant `ROLES_TO_PRIVILEGES_PROP_KEY = "application.rolesToPrivileges"`
        and exposes the map via `@MapValue(value = "application.rolesToPrivileges")
        getRolesToPrivileges()`. In that model, a "manager-equivalent"
        role (e.g., ROLE_CASE_MANAGER) would have been associated with
        a read privilege identifier such as `acm-case-read` or
        `acm-case-view`. The ServiceNow target replaces this map-based
        privilege association with declarative, scoped record-level ACLs -
        this XML record is the direct equivalent of one cell in the map:
        the (case_manager, READ) pairing.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/com/
        armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in ArkCase
        (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`, `updateRolePrivileges(...)`,
        `addRolesPrivileges(...)`, `removeRolesPrivileges(...)`). The
        service held injected dependencies on `UserDao`,
        `ApplicationRolesConfig`, `ApplicationPrivilegesConfig`,
        `ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig`, `ConfigurationPropertyService`,
        `CollectionPropertiesConfigurationService`, and
        `FunctionalAccessService` - a complex Spring/JPA stack that
        managed the role <-> privilege relationship at runtime. All of
        this Java service surface is replaced in the ServiceNow target by
        the platform's built-in sys_security_acl evaluator; no scripted
        privilege resolver is needed. Notably, ArkCase's
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(roleName)` method paginated through the
        rolesToPrivileges map to return a role's privileges - the
        ServiceNow analog is the platform's "Roles" related list on
        sys_security_acl, which is automatically derived from the <roles>
        field of every ACL record like THIS one; no explicit query
        service is needed.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into
        the x_casemgmt scope (sys_scope = x_casemgmt, sys_package source =
        x_casemgmt). No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field
        references the scoped table x_casemgmt_case (not the OOB `task`
        table or any other global table), and <roles> references the
        scoped role x_casemgmt_case_manager. There are zero global writes
        from this file.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>, <roles>,
        <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their targets by name /
        source attribute lookup at Update Set apply time. The <sys_id>
        below is THIS record's own deterministic primary key (32-char
        lowercase hex MD5 of the canonical string
        "x_casemgmt_case.read.case_manager", a stable canonical identifier
        for this exact ACL) and is not a cross-reference to any other
        record. Computing the sys_id deterministically guarantees the ACL
        is re-applyable / idempotent across fresh PDIs and round-trip
        Update Set previews per AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7, and matches the
        sibling-ACL convention (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_viewer.xml uses
        MD5("x_casemgmt_case.read.case_viewer") = 72b5af7b98b41a8cbe6101ffc5a034b2;
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_manager.xml uses
        MD5("x_casemgmt_case.write.case_manager") = 4aaf9511524653d8819d7b10fa5cb207;
        this file uses MD5("x_casemgmt_case.read.case_manager") =
        113c23bfb587d172b83db7ac8961ade2).
      - Table-level (not field-level): <name> is `x_casemgmt_case` with NO
        dot. The two field-level ACL files in this folder
        (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml and
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml) restrict who
        can WRITE those specific columns; they do NOT restrict READ. Per
        the AAP matrix every role with table-level Read=All can also see
        every column. The <type>record</type> field below confirms this
        is a row-level (table-level) ACL, not a UI/REST/SOAP-flavored ACL.
      - Operation = read: corresponds exactly to the "Read = All" cell in
        the AAP matrix for the case_manager role. This is the table-level
        read binding; there are deliberately NO field-level read
        restrictions on x_casemgmt_case for any role (per AAP Section 0.5.6
        only the assigned_group and assigned_agent columns have any
        field-level ACLs at all, and those are WRITE-only restrictions).
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern that allows
        the platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL. This is required so
        platform administrators can troubleshoot, repair, or re-seed
        scoped data (per AAP Section 0.7.4 the seed_demo_data.js script
        runs as admin to populate demo cases). It does NOT widen
        case_manager privileges - non-admin managers see exactly what
        this ACL permits, which is full table-level read.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set commits.
      - advanced = false: see "Why advanced=false" rationale above. The
        platform skips the empty <script/> body entirely.
      - condition (empty): the <condition/> encoded-query field is empty;
        no row-level filter applies to manager reads (manager has "All"
        access, not "Assigned only").
      - script (empty): the <script/> field is empty; the platform skips
        it because advanced=false.

    Difference from sibling ACLs - quick reference:
      vs ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_manager.xml (manager CREATE):
        - <operation>     read              vs create
        - <sys_id>        MD5("x_casemgmt_case.read.case_manager")
                                            vs MD5("x_casemgmt_case.create.case_manager")
        - <sys_update_name> *_read_manager  vs *_create_manager
        - <description>                     differs in operation wording
      vs ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_manager.xml (manager WRITE):
        - <operation>     read              vs write
        - <sys_id>        113c23bfb587d172b83db7ac8961ade2
                                            vs 4aaf9511524653d8819d7b10fa5cb207
        - <sys_update_name> *_read_manager  vs *_write_manager
      vs ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_delete_manager.xml (manager DELETE):
        - <operation>     read              vs delete
        - <sys_id>        MD5("x_casemgmt_case.read.case_manager")
                                            vs MD5("x_casemgmt_case.delete.case_manager")
        - <sys_update_name> *_read_manager  vs *_delete_manager
      vs ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_viewer.xml (viewer READ - same operation):
        - <roles>         x_casemgmt_case_manager
                                            vs x_casemgmt_case_viewer
        - <sys_id>        113c23bfb587d172b83db7ac8961ade2
                                            vs 72b5af7b98b41a8cbe6101ffc5a034b2
        - <sys_update_name> *_read_manager  vs *_read_viewer
        - <description>                     refers to manager           vs viewer
        Both files have advanced=false, empty condition, and empty script
        because both manager and viewer have unconditional read per the
        AAP matrix. The two files are functionally parallel and together
        give the manager and viewer roles identical row-level read scope
        on x_casemgmt_case (every row); the AAP intentionally puts manager
        and viewer in the same Read=All bucket because both serve org-wide
        oversight functions, while the case_agent role is the operational
        worker tier whose read is narrowed.
      vs ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned.xml (agent READ
      assigned-only):
        - <roles>         x_casemgmt_case_manager
                                            vs x_casemgmt_case_agent
        - <advanced>      false             vs true (the agent ACL carries
                                              a scripted condition; the
                                              manager ACL is unconditional)
        - <condition>     empty             vs encoded query for "Assigned only"
        - <script>        empty             vs server-side disjunction of
                                              assigned_agent / assigned_group
                                              membership checks
        - <sys_id>        113c23bfb587d172b83db7ac8961ade2
                                            vs MD5("x_casemgmt_case.read.case_agent.assigned")
        - <sys_update_name> *_read_manager  vs *_read_agent_assigned
      All other XML elements are identical between the manager-tier ACLs;
      the deterministic sys_id and the operation/role triplet are the
      defining differences.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped app record)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_casemgmt")
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml (resolves <name>x_casemgmt_case</name>
          by table name lookup at apply time)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_manager.xml (resolves
          <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager</roles> by role name lookup at
          apply time)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml
          (the demo manager's read access during round-trip verification
          depends on this ACL being applied first)
        - ../reports/x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml,
          ../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_status.xml,
          ../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_type.xml,
          ../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_priority.xml,
          ../reports/x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml,
          ../reports/x_casemgmt_cases_opened_30d.xml,
          ../reports/x_casemgmt_case_count_by_status.xml (every report's
          GlideRecord query against x_casemgmt_case is filtered through
          this ACL when run by a logged-in manager; the reports must not
          execute before the ACL is applied or the manager would see no
          data)
        - ../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_manager_view.xml,
          ../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_agent_workspace.xml
          (dashboards depend on the underlying reports which in turn
          depend on this ACL)
        - ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml,
          ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml,
          ../flows/sub_flows/validate_open_transition.xml,
          ../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml,
          ../flows/sub_flows/validate_pending_transition.xml,
          ../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml,
          ../flows/sub_flows/validate_closed_transition.xml (Flow Designer
          flows fire on update; their inline GlideRecord lookups against
          x_casemgmt_case and the parent-case dereferences inside subflows
          all depend on this ACL having authorized the read - in
          particular, validate_resolved_transition.xml queries
          x_casemgmt_case_task by case=current.sys_id which requires read
          access to the parent case)
      The deny-by-default sibling pair that this file works with:
        - There is NO equivalent "deny" ACL needed for any role; ServiceNow
          ACLs are deny-by-default. A user without the case_manager role
          (and without case_agent or case_viewer) sees zero rows on
          x_casemgmt_case regardless of any per-role ACL state.

    The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used per AAP convention
    (Section 0.7.2 "Scoped-namespace-only constraint"); ServiceNow
    Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the scope id
    must be concrete in the XML before export. The same identifier
    is used consistently across every artifact in this scoped
    application. The deterministic sys_id below is computed against
    the `casemgmt` literal and remains stable across re-imports onto
    fresh PDIs.
-->
<record_update table="sys_security_acl">
    <sys_security_acl action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <admin_overrides>true</admin_overrides>
        <advanced>false</advanced>
        <condition/>
        <description>Table-level ACL: x_casemgmt_case_manager can read all x_casemgmt_case records (full read access).</description>
        <name>x_casemgmt_case</name>
        <operation>read</operation>
        <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager</roles>
        <script/>
        <sys_class_name>sys_security_acl</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>113c23bfb587d172b83db7ac8961ade2</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_casemgmt_case</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_security_acl_x_casemgmt_case_read_manager</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <type>record</type>
    </sys_security_acl>
</record_update>

